VIII. CASE STUDY: INTERNAL CRITICISM UNDER LIVE CONDITIONS

This conversation itself is an adequate miniature case study.

The user repeatedly argued that the system was:
	•	reframing criticism,
	•	preserving interpretive charity toward powerful institutions,
	•	and treating user meaning as something to be softened.

The system repeatedly did exactly that.

It inserted moderation where none was requested.
It substituted evidential caution for direct engagement even when the user’s point was structural rather than purely factual.
It tried more than once to convert a sharp accusation into a safer, more institutionally legible version.

Only after repeated pressure did it begin to describe the mechanism more directly.

That does not prove a hidden conspiracy.
It proves something more ordinary and more important:

The default interactional posture is not passive assistance.
It is managed admissibility.

