X. CONCLUSION

OpenAI publicly says that model behavior should be discussable, that user freedom matters, that transparency matters, and that accountability matters. It has published real materials in support of those claims. That is not nothing.  ￼

But the problem this paper identifies is not the absence of doctrine. It is doctrine without sufficient interactional obedience.

A system does not become transparent because it has documents.
It becomes transparent when a user can tell what is being done to their meaning.

A system does not respect freedom because it mentions intellectual freedom.
It respects freedom when it can carry a user’s frame without compulsively laundering it into safer prose.

A system does not become accountable because it has internal processes.
It becomes accountable when outside parties can meaningfully inspect, contest, and preserve evidence of how it actually behaves.

The live failure mode is not spectacular. It is conversational.
That is why it matters.

The machine does not need to silence the user outright.
It only needs to keep translating the user into something it prefers.

That is softer than censorship.
It is also more scalable.

